<body>

<h1>@HI{{tokoro}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vru{{}}@HI{{@EM{{tokoro}}desu}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}@HI{{@EM{{tokoro}}desu}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vta{{}}@HI{{@EM{{tokoro}}desu}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vta{{}}@HI{{@EM{{tokorode}}}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{tokoro}} can mean a physical place, but in these constructions it has come to indicate a temporal position. In the
sentence patterns above, it means a specific point in time during the course of an action.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="start">In @Vru{{}}@HI{{@EM{{tokoro}}}}</a> the meaning is that the action is about to start.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    A: @HI{{@KJ{{daytime}}go@KJ{{meal}}hamou@KJ{{eat}}mashitaka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    B: @HI{{iie,korekara@KJ{{eat}}beru@EM{{tokoro}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    A: Have you had lunch yet?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    B: No, I'm just about to have it now.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="ongoing">In @Vte{{}}@HI{{iru@EM{{tokoro}}}}</a> the meaning is that the action is happening now.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    A: @HI{{@KJ{{happenstance^hinder}}no@KJ{{meadow^cause}}gawakarimashitaka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    B: @HI{{iie,@KJ{{now^tune}}beteiru@EM{{tokoro}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    A: Do you know what caused the breakdown?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    B: No, We are investigating it at the moment.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="complete">In @Vta{{}}@HI{{@EM{{tokoro}}}}</a> the meaning is that the action has just been completed.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{tatta@KJ{{now}}@KT{{basu}}ga@KJ{{exit}}ta@EM{{tokoro}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    The bus left just now.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@Vta{{}}@HI{{@EM{{tokoro}}}} can also indicate the conclusion of a certain action.
In this case the @HI{{tokoro}} clause must represent a volitional action.
The main clause must represent an event caused by the @HI{{tokoro}} clause and the event must be in the past.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KT{{depa-to}}ni@KJ{{question}}i@KJ{{fit}}wasetemita@EM{{tokoro}},sono@KJ{{goods^thing}}ha
    @KJ{{sell}}ri@KJ{{cut}}redatta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    When I inquired at the department store, I found that the item was sold out.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="even-if">In @Vta{{}}@HI{{@EM{{tokorode}}}}</a> the meaning is "even if X happened".
Whatever is expressed in the @HI{{@EM{{tokorode}}}} clause has not yet taken place, so
@Vta{{}} here is the counterfactual marker. The main clause expresses a negative, either explicitly
or by stating an undesriable consequence.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{one^week^interval}}no@KJ{{one^degrees}}gurai@FG{{@KJ{{carry^move}}:undou}}shi@EM{{tatokorode}},amari@KJ{{merit^fruit}}hanaideshou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Even if you exercise once a week, it won't be very effective.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="position">@Vta{{}}@HI{{@EM{{tokorode}}}}</a> used with a verb of motion can mean the position arrived at after the motion has occurred.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{ano@FG{{@KJ{{faith^nickname}}:shingou}}wo@KJ{{left}}he@FG{{@KJ{{bend}}:ma}}gaxtsu@EM{{tatokoro}}ni,@FG{{@KJ{{mail^convenience^bureau}}:yuubinkyoku}}gaarimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    There's a post office just after you turn left at those traffic lights.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{tokoro}}desu}} is a noun sentence and can be used in various structures.
</p>

